WEBVTT

00:06.018 --> 00:09.763
We're going to study tonight a very popular section of scripture.

00:09.823 --> 00:13.167
It's a parable entitled The Good Samaritan.

00:13.728 --> 00:18.935
I'm sure if you've been around church for any length of time, you've probably read this parable.

00:19.396 --> 00:26.765
It's widely known and any widely known parable is typically known because it's beautiful, but it's also messy.

00:27.426 --> 00:29.108
Messy stories get a traction.

00:29.208 --> 00:33.554
Beautiful stories are attractive and when they're tied together,

00:33.730 --> 00:35.332
They become famous.

00:35.392 --> 00:41.640
You've probably even heard the term good Samaritan before, no matter how connected you are to a church.

00:42.140 --> 00:45.364
Maybe you've even heard of the business called the Good Sam Club.

00:46.045 --> 00:52.173
Good Samaritans are people that we look for when we are in a difficult time or a difficult trouble.

00:52.673 --> 00:59.762
I remember as a young man, young boy actually at seven or eight years old, this story coming to life in my mind.

01:00.194 --> 01:07.083
My dad used to be a mechanic, and he was an on-call mechanic, which means he had one of those back in the days, like a pager.

01:07.223 --> 01:08.265
Anybody remember pagers?

01:09.607 --> 01:12.050
You'd beep your friends, those little codes.

01:12.871 --> 01:13.892
I didn't even forget the codes.

01:13.952 --> 01:15.434
I was like, four, one, three.

01:15.534 --> 01:17.056
I forget there was one for I Love You.

01:17.076 --> 01:24.406
My wife and I, back then, girlfriend and boyfriend, we had certain codes that she would know it's me.

01:25.007 --> 01:27.250
Well, my dad had this pager, this beeper,

01:27.522 --> 01:28.944
And I don't know what it was.

01:29.004 --> 01:33.930
I'm sure if you remember those, when you hear it vibrate or a beep, you just know what's going off.

01:34.571 --> 01:38.136
And I remember as a kid, we'd sit around the dinner table, sometimes we'd be on vacation.

01:38.196 --> 01:44.484
And at the artist and the most in like significant times, the pager would go off.

01:45.165 --> 01:47.448
And of course, my mom would say, ah, Rowan.

01:48.169 --> 01:50.652
And then he'd have to get up to get his work clothes on.

01:50.672 --> 01:55.378
And every once in a while, he would let us go for a ride with him and his work truck.

01:56.002 --> 02:09.781
And I remember just loving those trips in my dad's work truck, and he would go out, I remember this one night, it was like middle of the night, and I heard the, and I ran downstairs and I'm like, dad, I can't sleep, can I go with you?

02:09.801 --> 02:10.882
He's like, sure, come on in.

02:10.942 --> 02:13.325
And it was a long call.

02:14.086 --> 02:18.512
And I remember about halfway through thinking, okay, it's time to go home, I'm kind of tired.

02:19.273 --> 02:22.217
So when he was finished, we get in the truck and we're going home.

02:22.858 --> 02:25.161
And I just remember my dad saying to me, son, did you see that?

02:25.181 --> 02:25.682
And I said,

02:26.114 --> 02:26.435
What?

02:26.535 --> 02:27.376
What did you see?

02:27.436 --> 02:30.762
I saw blinking light off in the distance in a field.

02:31.543 --> 02:35.209
And he's like, I'm just interested, but I've got to turn this truck around and go look again.

02:35.229 --> 02:39.756
And then there in front of us, there was a car that was wrecked in the middle of the road.

02:39.796 --> 02:42.381
He's like, wait, wrecked car, blinking light.

02:42.421 --> 02:43.883
There might be somebody who needs help.

02:44.444 --> 02:45.926
And so he circled this truck around.

02:46.507 --> 02:48.671
He got out of the truck and walked off into the field.

02:48.711 --> 02:53.138
And I'm sitting there, which felt like several minutes.

02:53.314 --> 02:57.841
And all of a sudden, my dad opens the door and then he puts a woman in the truck next to me.

02:57.861 --> 02:59.103
He's like, son, move over, move over.

02:59.143 --> 03:00.606
This woman needs help.

03:00.666 --> 03:02.288
And I remember first, my first thought.

03:03.110 --> 03:10.522
My first thought was it was like a mom-aged, maybe a grandma-aged white American woman listening to her voice.

03:11.323 --> 03:18.855
And I remember as a young boy hanging out with some of my friends, when I was over at my white friend's house, sometimes their parents would treat me different.

03:19.897 --> 03:20.818
And I remember,

03:21.378 --> 03:25.745
Because of the color of my skin and the way I looked, just feeling out of place.

03:26.386 --> 03:30.112
And so my first impression was like, whoa, I better move over here.

03:30.132 --> 03:32.135
I'm not sure how she would feel next to me.

03:32.916 --> 03:36.983
And then I remember looking at her more closely, I could see the glass in her hair.

03:38.125 --> 03:40.448
Still, I'm thinking, oh man, she's really in bad shape.

03:40.929 --> 03:45.236
Looking even closer at her, there was blood on her ear and her cross her face.

03:45.356 --> 03:46.478
Man, this woman's in trouble.

03:46.818 --> 03:49.042
I remember trying to pick some of the glass out of her hair.

03:49.218 --> 03:50.820
giving her a napkin to wipe her face.

03:50.840 --> 03:54.544
And before I know it, the firemen were there and they carried her out of the truck.

03:55.485 --> 03:56.746
And I was back on my way.

03:56.786 --> 04:01.371
My dad getting inside beside me later that night saying, son, do you realize what just happened?

04:02.152 --> 04:04.615
We were able to help somebody who needed help.

04:05.616 --> 04:08.739
And the good Samaritan story just came upon me right in that moment.

04:09.400 --> 04:15.807
And I remembered all the elements of this rich story that I can't wait to share with you tonight.

04:16.267 --> 04:18.610
My hope is that this story reminds you

04:19.042 --> 04:28.113
that if it's not for the stories of the good Samaritan, that remind us that we've got to get out of our comfort zones if we're going to love like Jesus.

04:28.814 --> 04:42.290
If we're going to love like Jesus, we've got to step outside of what makes us comfortable and move towards compassion, not just a feeling of like, oh, I feel bad for that person, but move towards a place where you can step into somebody's pain.

04:42.946 --> 04:45.390
Help them when they need you the most.

04:45.430 --> 04:48.594
I want to ask you to just listen to this verse that I read to you.

04:48.635 --> 04:52.000
It's in the book of James chapter 2 verse 14 through 17.

04:52.320 --> 04:55.625
Here's what the Bible says.

04:56.406 --> 05:02.335
If someone claims to have faith but has no deeds, can such a faith save them?

05:03.196 --> 05:06.962
Suppose a brother or a sister is without clothes and daily food.

05:07.074 --> 05:15.346
If one of you says to them, go in peace, keep warm and well fed, but does nothing about their physical needs, what good is it?

05:15.747 --> 05:21.816
In the same way, faith by itself, if it's not accompanied by action, is dead.

05:22.978 --> 05:25.642
You see, this verse isn't telling us that our works save us.

05:26.443 --> 05:34.215
This verse reminds us that the works that come out of us to other people are a fruit of the faith that is deep within us.

05:35.256 --> 05:36.498
So what about you tonight?

05:36.770 --> 05:44.140
What's your recollection of the Good Samaritan story and where are you at in a place of moving from comfort to compassion?

05:44.561 --> 05:45.522
Here's what the Bible says.

05:45.542 --> 05:48.226
Let's read together what this story is all about.

05:48.286 --> 05:51.610
Luke chapter 10 verse 25, here's what the Bible says.

05:53.192 --> 05:57.979
On one occasion, an expert in the law stood up to test Jesus.

05:58.940 --> 06:02.585
Teacher, he asked, what must I do to inherit eternal life?

06:03.386 --> 06:05.169
Verse 26, what is written in the law?

06:05.209 --> 06:06.290
He replied.

06:06.498 --> 06:07.419
How do you read it?

06:08.140 --> 06:16.813
He answered, love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, and with all your strength, and with all your mind, and love your neighbor as yourself.

06:18.075 --> 06:22.381
You have answered correctly, Jesus replied, do this, and you will live.

06:23.322 --> 06:28.830
But he wanted to justify himself, so he asked Jesus, and who is my neighbor?

06:29.111 --> 06:31.053
Look with me back at verse 25 for a moment.

06:31.594 --> 06:34.258
What we see here is that there's an expert

06:34.658 --> 06:38.745
And there was different groupings of men in Old Testament tradition.

06:38.786 --> 06:41.491
You might remember Pharisees and Sadducees.

06:41.551 --> 06:46.239
And now this expert was referred to as a lawyer, somebody who was an expert in the law.

06:46.820 --> 06:53.292
Somebody who was so studied that people would come to him and say, hey, what's the interpretation of this Old Testament customer tradition?

06:53.673 --> 06:56.498
And they were known to be fluent in the law.

06:56.898 --> 06:59.120
And so this expert comes to Jesus.

06:59.201 --> 07:09.872
If you remember all around Luke chapter 10, throughout the gospels, you see these experts come to Jesus and test him or try him or ask him different questions.

07:10.653 --> 07:19.563
And it's hard for us to know what's in these individual's hearts when they ask Jesus these questions, but we can safely assume that he's trying Jesus.

07:20.364 --> 07:22.386
Now look with me closely, this expert

07:22.530 --> 07:24.733
asks his teacher, he calls him teacher.

07:24.753 --> 07:30.342
That word for teacher in the original language means master or elevated teacher.

07:30.422 --> 07:36.251
And so he understands how to respect Jesus, but he asked him, how do I get to eternal life?

07:37.072 --> 07:38.194
Eternal life, what is he asking?

07:38.214 --> 07:43.262
He's asking, how do I have a relationship with God that results in an eternity in heaven?

07:43.882 --> 07:46.867
Now, if you remember, he is an expert in the what?

07:48.009 --> 07:48.930
In the law, that's right.

07:48.950 --> 07:51.474
So what is he expecting Jesus to answer?

07:52.162 --> 07:56.767
He's probably expecting Jesus to point him back to himself.

07:57.487 --> 08:01.231
Well, I am the answer to that question, but Jesus answers him.

08:01.772 --> 08:05.536
If you look with me at verse 26, he answers him with a question.

08:06.597 --> 08:07.618
Probably shocks him.

08:08.098 --> 08:09.640
What is written in the what?

08:10.741 --> 08:13.984
He answers him with a question that points him back to his training.

08:14.645 --> 08:15.646
Shocks him, I'm sure.

08:16.166 --> 08:17.167
Well, what's written in the law?

08:17.187 --> 08:19.730
I didn't expect Jesus to answer me that way.

08:19.874 --> 08:25.361
How many times have you ever been asked a question and you felt a necessity to answer that question?

08:26.203 --> 08:40.562
If you're a parent and I want you to dial in really closely, if you're a leader in the room, I want you to dial in really closely because I believe we as parents and we as leaders in the room can often be put in weird circumstances when we're asked really hard questions.

08:41.784 --> 08:43.767
But I think we need to take a lesson here from Jesus.

08:44.748 --> 08:46.290
Instead of answering the question,

08:46.626 --> 08:49.770
He gives them another question to make him think all the more deeply.

08:50.451 --> 08:51.272
Have you ever tried that?

08:52.173 --> 08:53.355
Have you ever sat with one of your kids?

08:53.375 --> 08:54.356
You're asking you a question?

08:54.937 --> 08:56.679
You're like, oh, man, how am I going to answer this one?

08:57.881 --> 09:04.990
How can I make my child or this leader or person think more deeply before I just answer them?

09:05.471 --> 09:09.396
I think we can take cues from Jesus in the way that we lead our kids.

09:10.357 --> 09:13.842
I think we'd take cues from Jesus in the way that we lead people

09:14.082 --> 09:21.954
When we lead like Jesus led others, we see here that he answered this lawyer, this expert in a law, with how is it written?

09:21.994 --> 09:23.056
How would you answer?

09:23.096 --> 09:24.358
Look with me at verse 27.

09:24.398 --> 09:26.421
And the answer is very well.

09:26.681 --> 09:32.531
The Bible says he says, love the Lord, your God, with all of your heart, soul, mind, and strength.

09:33.172 --> 09:34.514
What does he answer the Lord with?

09:34.534 --> 09:36.196
He answers him with the Shema.

09:36.957 --> 09:42.546
And the Shema was this phrase that was repeated all throughout the Old Testament.

09:43.074 --> 09:47.760
If you remember, it was called the greatest of all the commandments, right?

09:48.280 --> 09:50.703
And the Shamal was something that was put in flactories.

09:50.743 --> 09:51.504
Remember flactories?

09:52.125 --> 09:55.189
They were put on the wrist of traditional Jewish people.

09:55.249 --> 09:57.412
They were put at the front doorpost of homes.

09:57.792 --> 09:59.955
It was something that was repeated twice daily.

09:59.975 --> 10:05.702
It was a phrase that was repeated so much because parents and leaders wanted it in the hearts of their kids.

10:06.182 --> 10:08.185
Could you imagine Christians in the room?

10:09.767 --> 10:12.370
If we truly lived as people that loved God,

10:12.770 --> 10:14.011
with everything inside of us?

10:14.872 --> 10:22.519
What would it change about us if we learned to love God with all of our heart, soul, mind, and strength?

10:23.100 --> 10:24.721
How differently would we live?

10:24.781 --> 10:30.026
How differently would we love our neighbors if we truly understood how to love God?

10:30.847 --> 10:42.418
How to truly allow his spirit to fill us in a way that influences our actions no matter what economic status a person held, no matter what skin color a person had,

10:42.594 --> 10:52.305
No matter what neighborhood a person lived in, no matter what a person looked like on the outside, if we loved God on our inside, it would affect how we love people on the outside.

10:52.325 --> 10:52.885
Do you follow me?

10:53.986 --> 10:59.212
And so it's important for us to remember the importance of this phrase in our own life.

10:59.713 --> 11:06.680
Now this next law that the lawyer quoted here in verse 27, he says, love your neighbor as yourself.

11:07.461 --> 11:11.826
Most Old Testament traditions called this second greatest commandment,

11:11.938 --> 11:19.726
the royal law, or the law that was the fruit of a change on the inside of a person.

11:19.866 --> 11:25.591
You see, when a person loves God, they're able to love others incredibly well.

11:26.352 --> 11:33.980
And so the lawyer answered, well, look with me at verse 28, Jesus says, you have answered correctly, do this and you will live.

11:34.020 --> 11:40.466
Now, of course, Jesus is setting this man up because who can follow the law with 100% accuracy?

11:41.346 --> 11:42.267
Nobody could.

11:42.567 --> 11:45.611
The law was created to show us our sin.

11:46.312 --> 11:57.846
The law was created in such a way where we would realize that we needed somebody or something greater than ourselves in order to overcome the issues that we battle with on the inside.

11:58.747 --> 12:05.235
And so the lawyer realized this, if you look with me here at verse 29, but he wanted to, you see it there?

12:05.996 --> 12:07.117
Justify himself.

12:07.157 --> 12:08.359
You can circle those words there.

12:08.859 --> 12:11.122
How many times have you wanted to justify yourself?

12:11.970 --> 12:28.315
Your face-to-face with a challenge, with a circumstance, maybe the Lord's convicted you on a habit or a way of lifestyle, and you realize it, and instead of submitting yourself to the Lord's way or will, you choose to justify yourself.

12:28.976 --> 12:31.159
Well, is there a different way?

12:31.540 --> 12:33.683
Or, well, what does the lawyer say here?

12:33.743 --> 12:37.068
Wanting to satisfy himself, he's asking, what does he say?

12:37.088 --> 12:38.130
Who is my neighbor?

12:38.626 --> 12:40.689
He thinks he's got Jesus pinned, right?

12:41.110 --> 12:41.931
Oh, I got him now.

12:42.291 --> 12:43.233
Who's my neighbor?

12:43.313 --> 12:55.131
According to Jewish law or Jewish tradition, the neighbor of the Jew would be a person who was like the good Jew or the righteous Jew or somebody who was culturally Jewish.

12:55.832 --> 13:00.178
And so the neighborhood of God for those people would consist of their own.

13:00.898 --> 13:08.807
So anybody outside of a person who was culturally Jewish or a righteous Jewish person would be or could be considered an enemy.

13:09.528 --> 13:13.813
Now a Samaritan was just that, the enemy.

13:14.634 --> 13:19.039
In some texts we'll see that a Samaritan was referred to like an animal.

13:20.020 --> 13:21.582
They were the enemy of enemies.

13:22.302 --> 13:29.010
You can read times in the New Testament where Samaritans would throw pigs at Jewish people to defile them.

13:29.538 --> 13:31.540
to create anger and hostilities in them.

13:31.560 --> 13:36.866
And you could read in some places where Jewish people were so antagonistic towards Samaritans.

13:36.886 --> 13:37.788
Who were Samaritans?

13:38.248 --> 13:43.955
They were Jews that were left during the exile and married outsiders.

13:44.856 --> 13:52.665
And so they were half-Jews and they were people that were looked down upon because they weren't 100% from a Jewish origin.

13:53.345 --> 13:57.330
And so these two groups were just at odds between each other.

13:57.730 --> 14:05.679
If you look with me here at verse 29, he wanted to justify himself, so he tried to define who his neighbor was or is.

14:05.719 --> 14:12.967
And in his narrow definition, we see Jesus explains the definition by telling him this parable.

14:13.127 --> 14:13.948
You ready for the parable?

14:14.809 --> 14:15.429
All right, here we go.

14:15.449 --> 14:18.052
Verse 30, look with me at Luke chapter 10.

14:18.573 --> 14:19.574
Here's what the Bible says.

14:21.476 --> 14:27.122
In reply, Jesus said, a man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho.

14:27.650 --> 14:35.440
And when he was attacked by robbers, they stripped him of his clothes, beat him, and went away, leaving him half dead.

14:35.460 --> 14:42.209
A priest happened to be going down the same road, and when he saw the man, he passed by on the other side.

14:42.269 --> 14:48.998
So to a Levite, when he came to the place and saw him, passed by on the other side, verse 33.

14:49.859 --> 14:52.503
Let's stop there, going back up to verse 30 with me.

14:52.983 --> 14:55.026
If you look here, we see a man.

14:55.874 --> 14:58.738
The Bible says Jesus told a story about a given man.

14:58.939 --> 15:06.830
We would assume that this was a Jewish man, a man who was walking down this road from Jerusalem to Jericho.

15:07.251 --> 15:11.838
Now, if you look up this route, it's called the way of blood.

15:12.859 --> 15:17.145
And it was called the way of blood because it was such a dangerous path to take.

15:17.165 --> 15:22.994
17 miles long, most historians would say at the time the road was very narrow.

15:23.362 --> 15:30.834
It was platted through all of these different valleys and mountaintops and clefs that were written or kind of put in between.

15:30.934 --> 15:35.061
And so it was an easy place to find trouble for yourself.

15:35.863 --> 15:38.928
And so this man is on his way from Jerusalem to Jericho.

15:39.268 --> 15:45.879
And while he's going down, he's beaten, he's stripped naked, he's robbed, and he's left for dead.

15:46.660 --> 15:50.066
And what we see here is that there was a priest who passed by.

15:50.498 --> 15:56.225
Now, I'm sure you might remember a priest as a person who would have responsibilities in the temple.

15:57.186 --> 16:04.155
He was a person who would understand religiously what he ought to do when he sees a person in need.

16:04.556 --> 16:05.417
He would have the training.

16:05.437 --> 16:06.498
He would have the expertise.

16:07.019 --> 16:09.962
He would have the understanding to know, wow, there's a person in need.

16:10.643 --> 16:13.066
I should do what I can do to help him.

16:13.086 --> 16:13.968
But what does the Bible say?

16:14.668 --> 16:19.154
He saw him, but he passes by on the other side.

16:19.842 --> 16:21.344
Now remember that narrow road.

16:21.405 --> 16:23.708
It's not like he could fake like he didn't see him.

16:24.189 --> 16:27.013
He saw him, but he didn't really see him see him.

16:27.034 --> 16:28.235
Does that make sense?

16:28.255 --> 16:32.001
He didn't see him to the point where it affected him with what he saw.

16:32.042 --> 16:35.247
Do you remember the last time that you saw something that affected you?

16:36.709 --> 16:41.877
Can you remember the last time that you were moved to action based upon what you've seen?

16:43.740 --> 16:47.346
Can you remember the last time that you saw something that should have moved you to action?

16:48.354 --> 16:53.059
let you allow it to just leave you cold and leave you actionless.

16:54.020 --> 17:01.668
I can file through story after story in my own mind of regrets of moments where I should have acted and didn't act.

17:02.528 --> 17:03.850
And I'm sure you could as well.

17:04.751 --> 17:07.474
And tonight is a moment of reminder for us.

17:07.994 --> 17:15.762
This priest saw something that he, that should have led him to action, but he was left and in a place of inaction.

17:16.066 --> 17:17.207
Now, we see the priests.

17:17.227 --> 17:18.930
Secondarily, we see a Levite.

17:19.450 --> 17:23.916
Now, a Levite is a person who is also from the same tribe from which priests come.

17:24.617 --> 17:30.043
Also, he's a person who has responsibilities in the temple, and he's in the same place.

17:31.125 --> 17:38.093
He's passing by this man who's half dead, this man who's been robbed, a man who's been left for dead.

17:39.075 --> 17:39.735
What do we see here?

17:40.356 --> 17:41.798
He passes by on the other side.

17:41.818 --> 17:45.042
He sees him, but there's no action, and there's

17:45.186 --> 17:46.087
no response.

17:47.189 --> 17:52.638
Now you might be wondering, why would a priest and why would a Levite find themselves doing this?

17:52.658 --> 17:57.205
You notice back in verse 30 that he was close to being dead, right?

17:57.646 --> 18:02.994
There were laws that prevented a priest from touching something that was dead.

18:03.034 --> 18:07.361
And so you might look on and say, well, maybe the priest thought he was dead.

18:08.863 --> 18:10.706
Now this could be a reasonable

18:10.786 --> 18:13.730
or a plausible excuse for us, but we don't know what was in his mind.

18:14.150 --> 18:17.494
All that we know is that we realize the man was left half dead.

18:18.295 --> 18:20.979
Now we also know that there's a law of mercy.

18:21.660 --> 18:24.743
Now the law of mercy extends to a priest or a Levite.

18:25.224 --> 18:36.418
When they have a reasonable suspicion to believe the person is still alive, they could step into a situation and help an individual because of that law of mercy.

18:36.458 --> 18:39.602
Now you realize if a priest touches

18:39.906 --> 18:46.395
somebody who's dead, they would have to sit out during a time of purification for seven full days.

18:47.356 --> 18:54.506
And so these two men allowed themselves to take an excuse to allow them to pass by.

18:54.546 --> 18:56.729
Could you imagine the excuses that were running in their mind?

18:57.870 --> 19:00.754
Could you imagine the excuses that would probably run through your mind?

19:02.116 --> 19:03.058
I just got a new suit.

19:03.759 --> 19:05.601
I'm not sure if I want that suit to get bloody.

19:06.723 --> 19:07.544
I got to let that one go.

19:07.564 --> 19:09.266
Oh, my wife is, my wife is

19:09.410 --> 19:16.945
is paging me, my beeper, or calling me, sending me a text, whatever it is, and I've got to get home.

19:17.426 --> 19:20.132
I've got a baseball game for the kids to run to.

19:20.172 --> 19:25.202
Maybe he might say, the priest might say, oh, let the Levite, I saw a Levite coming.

19:25.634 --> 19:29.979
